<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>
<project xmlns="http://maven.apache.org/POM/4.0.0"
         xmlns:xsi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema-instance"
         xsi:schemaLocation="http://maven.apache.org/POM/4.0.0 https://maven.apache.org/xsd/maven-4.0.0.xsd">
  <modelVersion>4.0.0</modelVersion>

  <!--
    Chapter 39 companion (Changing Code Without Breaking It). Puts the chapter's one invariant —
    preserve behaviour, verify with tests, move in small steps — into one buildable module at two of
    the four scales it teaches. A LegacyShippingCalculator news up its own rate source and clock, so it
    cannot be tested as written (Feathers: legacy code is code without tests). An EXTRACT INTERFACE
    seam (RateTable) lets a test double slot in without editing the call site, and a characterization
    test pins the legacy method's CURRENT behaviour — including a faithfully-preserved rounding quirk —
    before anything changes. ShippingCalculator is then the modernized refactor: the same behaviour
    expressed with a record, a sealed Quote hierarchy + pattern-matching switch, Optional, and streams
    (the modern-Java idioms that supersede some 2018-era manual catalog steps). A behaviour-preservation
    test proves the refactor changes structure, not results, for every parcel. The StranglerRouter is a
    routing façade that sends each request to the legacy or the modern path behind a flag — the system
    scale's incremental cutover sketched small, with a test driving both routes and the rollback. Zero
    runtime dependencies — JDK only — so it dogfoods the book and builds fast and green. The contracts
    are machine-checked by the `quality` profile (Checkstyle + SpotBugs, Chapter 16).
  -->
  <parent>
    <groupId>org.acme.storefront</groupId>
    <artifactId>companion-code</artifactId>
    <version>1.0.0-SNAPSHOT</version>
  </parent>

  <artifactId>refactoring-legacy-modernization</artifactId>
  <name>Chapter 39 — Changing Code Without Breaking It (refactoring-legacy-modernization)</name>

  <dependencies>
    <dependency>
      <groupId>org.junit.jupiter</groupId>
      <artifactId>junit-jupiter</artifactId>
      <scope>test</scope>
    </dependency>
    <dependency>
      <groupId>org.assertj</groupId>
      <artifactId>assertj-core</artifactId>
      <scope>test</scope>
    </dependency>
  </dependencies>

  <!--
    Static-analysis rule gates from Chapter 16, opt-in via `-Pquality` so the default build stays
    fast. The maven-checkstyle-plugin ships an OLD bundled engine (Checkstyle 9.3); we override it to
    the pinned engine via a plugin-level dependency — the "two-pin" lesson (the build plugin and the
    analyzer engine are separate versions). This module is a direct child of the companion-code root,
    which pins no quality profile of its own, so the profile is declared here (the same shape the
    Chapter 19 and Chapter 09 modules use) and reads the config under this module's config/ dir.
  -->
  <profiles>
    <profile>
      <id>quality</id>
      <build>
        <plugins>
          <plugin>
            <groupId>org.apache.maven.plugins</groupId>
            <artifactId>maven-checkstyle-plugin</artifactId>
            <version>3.6.0</version>
            <dependencies>
              <dependency>
                <groupId>com.puppycrawl.tools</groupId>
                <artifactId>checkstyle</artifactId>
                <version>10.26.1</version>
              </dependency>
            </dependencies>
            <configuration>
              <configLocation>config/checkstyle/checkstyle.xml</configLocation>
              <consoleOutput>true</consoleOutput>
              <failOnViolation>true</failOnViolation>
              <violationSeverity>error</violationSeverity>
              <includeTestSourceDirectory>true</includeTestSourceDirectory>
            </configuration>
            <executions>
              <execution>
                <id>checkstyle-check</id>
                <phase>verify</phase>
                <goals>
                  <goal>check</goal>
                </goals>
              </execution>
            </executions>
          </plugin>
          <!--
            SpotBugs: the bytecode vantage point (Chapter 16) — complementary to Checkstyle's source
            view. This module ships ONE deliberate legacy counter-example (LegacyShippingCalculator)
            whose representation-exposure finding is part of the teaching point: the legacy class hands
            back its internal mutable list of applied surcharges, the kind of latent leak the
            modernized refactor closes with an immutable snapshot. So the exclude filter carries one
            narrowly-scoped, reasoned suppression (the leaked surcharge list on the legacy type). That
            is the chapter's own "suppress with a documented reason, never disable a detector"
            discipline (Chapter 16) made concrete — not a way to hide a real defect; the modern
            ShippingCalculator carries no such finding.
          -->
          <plugin>
            <groupId>com.github.spotbugs</groupId>
            <artifactId>spotbugs-maven-plugin</artifactId>
            <version>4.9.3.0</version>
            <configuration>
              <effort>Max</effort>
              <threshold>Medium</threshold>
              <includeTests>false</includeTests>
              <excludeFilterFile>config/spotbugs/spotbugs-exclude.xml</excludeFilterFile>
            </configuration>
            <executions>
              <execution>
                <id>spotbugs-check</id>
                <phase>verify</phase>
                <goals>
                  <goal>check</goal>
                </goals>
              </execution>
            </executions>
          </plugin>
        </plugins>
      </build>
    </profile>
  </profiles>
</project>
